sections = [
    "\n## 11. Market Research — Minimalist Integration Candidates\n",
    "\nResearch into how best-in-class behavioral and cooking apps solve retention, habit formation, and in-session engagement — filtered through Sous's radical simplicity constraint.\n",
    "\n> **GATE:** No feature is built unless it clears all three bars: **(a) zero new screens**, **(b) maximum one new UI element**, **(c) directly increases cooks-per-week**. Features that fail any gate go to the Parking Lot (Section 12).\n",
    "\n### Pestle — Read-Aloud Step Narration\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Source** | Pestle (iOS recipe manager) |\n| **Feature** | Hands-free audio narration of each cook step, triggered automatically when a timer ends or the user taps a play button |\n| **Sous adaptation** | Add a speaker icon to the guided cook step card. Tap once to have the step read aloud. No new screen — the icon lives inline with the existing step text. Voice uses device TTS with a calm, neutral tone. |\n| **Minimalism filter** | Passes. One new icon, no new screen. Adds zero cognitive load for users who don't tap it. |\n| **Effort** | Low — Web Speech API or native TTS, no backend changes required |\n| **Moat strengthened** | Content moat (guided cook quality), behavioral moat (hands-free cooking reduces abandonment) |\n",
    "\n### Duolingo — Streak Freeze\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Source** | Duolingo (language learning) |\n| **Feature** | One free streak protection per week, automatically applied when the user misses a day. Earned through challenge completion, not purchased. |\n| **Sous adaptation** | Already referenced in Section 4.1. Implementation: store one `streakFreezeAvailable` boolean per user. Auto-apply on missed day if true. Display as a small shield icon on the streak counter — not a separate screen. |\n| **Minimalism filter** | Passes. One icon state change, no new screen. The freeze is silent — it just works. |\n| **Effort** | Low — one boolean in user state, one conditional in streak calculation |\n| **Moat strengthened** | Behavioral moat (protects the streak's loss-aversion psychology; reduces churn at streak-break moments) |\n",
    "\n### Headspace — Celebration Variants\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Source** | Headspace (meditation) |\n| **Feature** | Win screen celebrations vary based on milestone type — first cook, streak milestone, new cuisine, personal best time — each with a distinct animation and coach message |\n| **Sous adaptation** | The win screen already exists. Extend the coach message and confetti color/pattern based on the cook context. No new screen — the win screen gains conditional content. Five variants: first cook, streak milestone (7/14/30), new cuisine unlocked, fastest cook, recipe gift sent. |\n| **Minimalism filter** | Passes. No new screens or UI elements — only the content of the existing win screen changes. |\n| **Effort** | Low-Medium — logic to detect variant type + 5 coach message sets + animation variants |\n| **Moat strengthened** | Behavioral moat (richer reward loop deepens habit formation at key milestones) |\n",
    "\n### Yummly — Substitution Nudge\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Source** | Yummly (recipe discovery) |\n| **Feature** | Inline ingredient substitution suggestions appear when a recipe calls for something the user has previously indicated they don't have or can't eat |\n| **Sous adaptation** | During guided cook, if a step mentions an ingredient the user has marked unavailable (via a long-press gesture), show an inline substitution chip. One chip, inline, dismissible. No new screen. Substitution data is pre-authored per ingredient, not AI-generated at runtime. |\n| **Minimalism filter** | Passes. One new gesture (long-press on ingredient) and one new chip type — both are already familiar UI patterns in Sous. |\n| **Effort** | Medium — requires ingredient tagging in cook steps + substitution lookup table + user unavailability store |\n| **Moat strengthened** | Content moat (authored substitution data is non-trivial to replicate), data moat (ingredient unavailability signals refine preference vector) |\n",
    "\n### Noom — Micro-Lesson\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Source** | Noom (behavior-change health app) |\n| **Feature** | 60-second educational cards appear between major milestones, teaching one concept per session (e.g., why resting meat matters, how acid balances fat) |\n| **Sous adaptation** | After the win screen, before returning to Today, show one optional cuisine fact card — a single sentence with a visual. Skippable with one tap. Content is drawn from the existing hack chip and cuisine fact database already authored per dish. No new content required initially. |\n| **Minimalism filter** | Passes. One transitional card between existing screens — not a new screen in the nav, just a moment between flows. Skip is the primary action; reading is secondary. |\n| **Effort** | Low — content already exists in hack chips; requires only a transitional card component and display logic |\n| **Moat strengthened** | Content moat (positions Sous as cooking education, not just cooking execution), behavioral moat (small knowledge rewards between cooks compound into perceived expertise) |\n",
    "\n### Mela — Recipe Scaling\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Source** | Mela (iOS recipe app) |\n| **Feature** | One-tap serving size adjustment that scales all ingredient quantities proportionally |\n| **Sous adaptation** | Add a serving size control (+/- stepper) to the recipe grab screen (the ingredient list). Ingredient quantities scale inline. No new screen. Default is 2 servings. Range is 1-6. |\n| **Minimalism filter** | Passes. One stepper control on an existing screen. The stepper is hidden until the user taps the serving count, preserving default simplicity. |\n| **Effort** | Medium — requires ingredient quantities to be stored as numeric values with units in the data layer (currently some are prose); data migration needed before UI |\n| **Moat strengthened** | Content moat (requires structured ingredient data that competitors must also build), behavioral moat (reduces friction for cooking for different group sizes) |\n",
    "\n### Centr — Progressive Difficulty\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Source** | Centr (Chris Hemsworth fitness app) |\n| **Feature** | Each week's plan is slightly harder than the last — longer sessions, more complex movements — calibrated to the user's demonstrated capability |\n| **Sous adaptation** | After 10 cooks in a cuisine, Sous begins surfacing dishes with one additional complexity tag (more steps, longer prep, more techniques). The progression is silent — no announcement, no difficulty label. The user notices they're cooking more ambitious dishes without being told. |\n| **Minimalism filter** | Passes. Zero new UI. Progression is expressed entirely through which dishes surface in recommendations, not through any visible complexity indicator. |\n| **Effort** | Low — requires a `complexity_tier` field on side dish records (already partially encoded in `skill_level`) + one additional scorer weight in the pairing engine |\n| **Moat strengthened** | Engine moat (complexity progression requires the full cook history to be meaningful — non-portable), data moat (demonstrated skill calibration is a unique signal no competitor has) |\n",
    "\n---\n",
    "\n## 12. Ambitious Ideas Parking Lot\n",
    "\nIdeas that are too large, too speculative, or too infrastructure-heavy for the current stage — but worth preserving so they can be revisited deliberately.\n",
    "\n> **Review cadence:** Monthly. Present the top 3 ranked by strategic fit to the founder. Promote to active planning only if prerequisites are met and the idea clears the minimalism gate.\n",
    "\n### AR Plating Assistant\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | IKEA Place (AR furniture preview), modern food styling apps |\n| **What** | Point your camera at an empty plate and see a visual overlay of how to plate the finished dish — sauce placement, garnish positioning, component arrangement |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires real-time computer vision, AR overlay rendering, and a library of 3D or 2D plating templates per dish |\n| **Upside** | Transforms the win moment into a shareable, beautiful plate — drives organic social sharing and positions Sous as premium |\n| **Prerequisites** | Stable AR framework (WebXR or native ARKit/ARCore), plating template library for top 50 dishes, 60fps performance on mid-range devices |\n| **Risk** | High implementation complexity; most users may not bother; requires permissions that increase friction at a critical moment |\n| **Status** | PARKED — revisit when catalog reaches 300+ dishes and social sharing is validated as an acquisition channel |\n",
    "\n### Voice-Guided Cooking *(UNDER CONSIDERATION)*\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Amazon Alexa cooking skills, Google Assistant recipes, Pestle read-aloud |\n| **What** | Fully hands-free cooking mode: the app reads each step aloud, listens for \"next step\" or \"repeat that\" voice commands, and manages timers without any screen touches |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires a wake-word listener running in background, robust speech recognition in a noisy kitchen environment, and careful UX to avoid false positives |\n| **Upside** | Dramatically reduces friction during active cooking — the hardest moment to interact with a screen; potentially the highest-impact accessibility and usability improvement available |\n| **Prerequisites** | Pestle-style TTS (Section 11) validated and adopted; speech recognition accuracy benchmarked in kitchen noise conditions; push notification permission already granted |\n| **Risk** | Background audio processing drains battery; speech recognition errors mid-cook are disruptive; requires significant testing across device microphone quality |\n| **Status** | UNDER CONSIDERATION — TTS read-aloud (Section 11) is the prerequisite MVP; if adoption is strong, voice command input is the logical next step |\n",
    "\n### AI-Generated Weekly Meal Plans\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Noom weekly program, Centr weekly plan, Mealime |\n| **What** | Each Sunday, Sous generates a personalized 5-night meal plan based on your preference vector, recent cooks, upcoming calendar (optional), and nutritional balance goals |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires a planning-layer AI that reasons across multiple days, ingredient overlap, nutritional balance, and variety — significantly more complex than single-session pairing |\n| **Upside** | Captures the \"what should I cook this week\" decision — an even higher-friction moment than \"what should I cook tonight\" — and extends Sous's value from daily to weekly |\n| **Prerequisites** | Preference vector maturity (30+ cooks per user), ingredient intelligence layer (Section 6.5), calendar integration for context-awareness |\n| **Risk** | Plans feel generic if preference data is thin; week-level commitment may conflict with Sous's spontaneous craving model; increases product complexity significantly |\n| **Status** | PARKED — revisit after preference vector is validated as meaningful (30-day cohort data required) |\n",
    "\n### Social Recipe Marketplace\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Etsy (creator marketplace), Gumroad, Substack |\n| **What** | Experienced Sous users can publish their own guided cook flows — complete with steps, timers, hack chips, and photos — and optionally charge for premium recipes |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires creator tools, content moderation, payment infrastructure, quality standards enforcement, and a two-sided marketplace dynamic |\n| **Upside** | Dramatically expands catalog without Sous authoring every recipe; creates a creator economy around cooking; potential revenue stream beyond subscription |\n| **Prerequisites** | Community tab shipped and active (30-day unlock), 10,000+ MAU to provide creator audience, content quality framework to prevent low-quality submissions |\n| **Risk** | Quality control is extremely difficult; low-quality recipes damage trust in the recommendation engine; creator economics require critical mass to be meaningful |\n| **Status** | PARKED — not before 10k MAU and Community tab validation |\n",
    "\n### Smart Device Integration\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Drop connected kitchen scale, BRAVA smart oven, Anova sous vide |\n| **What** | Sous connects to smart kitchen devices — ovens, scales, thermometers — and controls or monitors them directly from the guided cook flow. Timers trigger device preheating; temperature sensors pause the step until target is reached. |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires integrations with a fragmented hardware ecosystem, Bluetooth/Wi-Fi pairing UX, and real-time device state management — all before the software product is proven |\n| **Upside** | Closes the loop between digital guidance and physical cooking in a way no app competitor can match; creates deep lock-in through hardware dependency |\n| **Prerequisites** | Software product validated and retained (40%+ week-4 retention), partnership with at least one smart device manufacturer, SDK access |\n| **Risk** | Hardware fragmentation makes maintenance expensive; users without smart devices are excluded; raises expectations for reliability that are difficult to meet |\n| **Status** | PARKED — post-Series A at earliest |\n",
    "\n### Computer Vision Real-Time Feedback\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Whisk ingredient recognition, Yummly dish identification, PlatePal |\n| **What** | During guided cook, point your camera at the pan and receive real-time feedback: \"your onions aren't caramelized yet — keep going\" or \"that looks perfectly browned — move to next step\" |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires low-latency on-device vision inference, a visual state classification model per cooking step, and an extensive labeled training dataset of intermediate cooking states |\n| **Upside** | Eliminates the most common failure mode in cooking — misjudging doneness — and is completely differentiated from any existing competitor |\n| **Prerequisites** | Training dataset of 10,000+ labeled intermediate cooking state images, on-device model (not API-dependent), 60fps inference on 3-year-old devices |\n| **Risk** | Lighting conditions in home kitchens are highly variable and will degrade model accuracy; false confidence could cause food safety issues |\n| **Status** | PARKED — requires dedicated ML research investment; not feasible pre-Series A |\n",
    "\n### Cooking Tournaments\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Duolingo leagues, Peloton challenges, Top Chef format |\n| **What** | Monthly themed tournaments: \"Best Italian Side Dish — July.\" Users cook a designated dish, submit a photo, and community votes on the best result. Top 3 win featured placement in other users' quest cards. |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires community moderation, voting infrastructure, prize/recognition mechanics, and a large enough user base for voting to feel meaningful |\n| **Upside** | Creates a recurring engagement spike at the start of each month; gives ambitious users a high-status goal beyond personal streaks; generates UGC that can feed the content moat |\n| **Prerequisites** | Community tab shipped, 5,000+ MAU in the same cuisine cohort to make voting competitive, moderation tooling |\n| **Risk** | Small user base makes tournaments feel empty; competitive dynamics may alienate users who cook for personal enjoyment, not performance |\n| **Status** | PARKED — not before Community tab and 5k MAU threshold |\n",
    "\n### Offline Mode *(UNDER CONSIDERATION)*\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Spotify offline playlists, Google Maps offline areas, Mela local storage |\n| **What** | Users can save up to 5 guided cook flows for offline use. The app downloads all steps, timers, and media in advance. Cooking works fully without an internet connection. |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires a local storage strategy for structured cook data, media caching, sync logic for cook completions when back online, and storage budget management |\n| **Upside** | Removes a friction point for users cooking in kitchens with poor Wi-Fi; signals reliability and polish; meaningfully expands use cases (camping, travel, power outages) |\n| **Prerequisites** | Service worker infrastructure, IndexedDB or SQLite on device, sync queue for offline cook completions |\n| **Risk** | Cached content can go stale if recipes are updated; storage limits vary by device; adds complexity to the data layer |\n| **Status** | UNDER CONSIDERATION — relatively low risk compared to other parking lot items; worth scoping once the guided cook data model is stable |\n",
    "\n### White-Label B2B\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Whisk (licensed to Samsung), SideChef (licensed to appliance brands), Yummly Pro |\n| **What** | License the Sous engine and guided cook UX to a kitchen appliance brand, grocery chain, or meal kit company under their own brand. Their catalog, their colors, Sous's brain. |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires a multi-tenant architecture, brand theming system, enterprise sales motion, SLA commitments, and legal/commercial infrastructure far beyond the current stage |\n| **Upside** | B2B revenue is less volatile than consumer subscription; partnership with a major grocery chain could provide distribution and catalog data |\n| **Prerequisites** | Stable, well-documented API, multi-tenant data isolation, reference customer (ideally a recognizable brand), legal entity and contracts infrastructure |\n| **Risk** | B2B sales cycles are long and expensive; white-label deals can distract from consumer product focus at a critical growth stage; partner priorities may conflict with product vision |\n| **Status** | PARKED — post-product-market-fit; not before consumer retention metrics are proven |\n",
    "\n### Seasonal Sourcing Intelligence\n",
    "\n| Field | Detail |\n|---|---|\n| **Inspiration** | Seasonal Food Guide, Eatwell (UK), Ottolenghi seasonal menus |\n| **What** | Sous boosts side dishes that feature ingredients currently in peak season in the user's region. A small \"in season\" label appears on the result card. Seasonal data updates monthly by hemisphere. |\n| **Why ambitious** | Requires regional ingredient seasonality data across all supported cuisines and geographies, user location (or region inference), and monthly data refresh pipeline |\n| **Upside** | Meaningfully improves ingredient quality for users who source locally; differentiates Sous from apps with purely algorithmic recommendations; aligns with growing sustainability values |\n| **Prerequisites** | Location permission or region selection, ingredient-level seasonality dataset (monthly x ingredient x region), integration into the pairing engine as a soft scorer |\n| **Risk** | Seasonality data is complex (microclimates, retail availability vs. farm availability); incorrect seasonal labels erode trust; low priority for urban users who shop at supermarkets year-round |\n| **Status** | PARKED — valuable but low urgency; revisit when ingredient-level data is already structured for scaling (prerequisite for Mela scaling in Section 11) |\n",
    "\n---\n",
    "\n*— End of Strategic Design Document —*\n",
]

